<TITLE> Kenyan Muslims vow weeks of protests </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 NAIROBI, Aug 31 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Kenyan Muslims vowed on Friday to hold weeks of protests against what they call arbitrary arrests, illegal deportation, torture and harassment in the east African nation. A day after marching on police headquarters in Nairobi, Muslims and grassroots activists held a rally at the capital's biggest mosque and pledged to continue their demonstrations. "This is just the beginning. We are assembling constitutional lawyers to meet this week. ... We will protest at Freedom Corner in Nairobi, we will go to the U.S. embassy," said Al-Amin Kimathi, chairman of Kenya's Muslim Human Rights Forum. Kenyan security forces arrested scores of people on the Somali border in January and February after allied Somali and Ethiopian troops chased Islamist fighters out of Mogadishu. The Rights Forum launched a petition naming 18 Kenyans it said were among more than 150 people then sent to Somalia, Ethiopia and Guantanamo Bay. Rights groups say they were held without charge and some were tortured. "We expect to collect in excess of one million signatures," Kimathi said as he passed around copies of the petition. Kenyan Muslims accuse their government of being swayed by the United States, which says Somalia's Islamist movement was hosting al Qaeda suspects it blames for the deadly bombings of its embassies in Kenya and Tanzania in 1998. Kenyan government officials were not immediately available to comment on the threat of more protests. A US official in Nairobi said Washington was committed to working with regional partners to oppose terrori
